      <h2 class="sec-head">🔄 Why We Drifted Away From Simple</h2>

      <p>
        For the better part of three decades, wellness culture has been defined by intensity. The harder the workout, the stricter the diet, the more dramatic the transformation — the more credible the approach seemed. Entire industries were built on the premise that feeling better required suffering first.
      </p>

      <p>
        The data tells a different story. A landmark study published in the <em>British Journal of Health Psychology</em> found that people who built small, low-effort daily habits were significantly more likely to maintain positive health changes at the 12-month mark than those who attempted large behavioral overhauls. The reason is neurological: the brain resists dramatic change. It embraces gradual, repeated patterns.
      </p>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p class="pq-text">"Sustainable wellness is not achieved in 30-day challenges. It is achieved in 30-day routines — practiced quietly, consistently, and without drama, until they become as automatic as breathing."</p>
        <span class="pq-source">— Harvard Health Letter, 2025 Annual Habits &amp; Longevity Review</span>
      </div>

      <p>
        The lifestyle lesson many people are rediscovering is this: <strong>you don't need a new system. You need to actually do the old, proven ones.</strong> Morning hydration. Consistent sleep. Natural food. Daily movement. And — increasingly — specific natural compounds that support what your body is already trying to do.
      </p>

      <h2 class="sec-head">🌤️ The 6 Pillars of Rediscovered Daily Wellness</h2>

      <p>
        Across cultures known for longevity and low rates of lifestyle disease — from Okinawa, Japan to Sardinia, Italy to the Nicoya Peninsula in Costa Rica — researchers have identified the same foundational lifestyle patterns. They are not complicated. What makes them powerful is their <em>daily repetition.</em>
      </p>

      <div class="habit-grid">
        <div class="habit-card">
          <div class="hc-icon">💧</div>
          <div class="hc-title">Morning Hydration Ritual</div>
          <div class="hc-text">Starting the day with 16–24oz of water — often with natural additions like lemon or herbal extracts — activates digestion, clears metabolic waste, and signals the body to begin active mode.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="habit-card">
          <div class="hc-icon">🌿</div>
          <div class="hc-title">Natural Compound Intake</div>
          <div class="hc-text">Polyphenols, adaptogens, and fermented compounds consumed consistently — not in megadoses, but daily — have been shown to meaningfully support metabolism, gut health, and cellular repair over weeks and months.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="habit-card">
          <div class="hc-icon">🚶</div>
          <div class="hc-title">Low-Intensity Daily Movement</div>
          <div class="hc-text">Daily walks of 20–40 minutes have been shown in multiple studies to reduce visceral fat, regulate blood sugar, and improve sleep quality more reliably than sporadic intense exercise.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="habit-card">
          <div class="hc-icon">🍽️</div>
          <div class="hc-title">Mindful, Whole-Food Eating</div>
          <div class="hc-text">Not calorie counting. Prioritizing unprocessed, whole foods at consistent meal times regulates hunger hormones, reduces inflammation, and supports the gut microbiome — the engine of metabolic health.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="habit-card">
          <div class="hc-icon">😴</div>
          <div class="hc-title">Consistent Sleep Windows</div>
          <div class="hc-text">Going to bed and waking at similar times preserves circadian alignment, regulates cortisol, and protects the hormonal environment that determines whether the body burns or stores fat.</div>
        </div>

        <div class="habit-card">
          <div class="hc-icon">🧘</div>
          <div class="hc-title">Intentional Stillness</div>
          <div class="hc-text">Five to ten minutes of deliberate quiet daily lowers cortisol levels measurably. Chronic cortisol elevation is one of the most underdiagnosed drivers of stubborn weight gain and fatigue.</div>
        </div>
